Operational Frameworks

⸻

1. Absence → Bridge → Presence (ABP Protocol)

Purpose: Convert negative bonding into constructive alignment

Steps:
	1.	Absence: Establish shared lack
	2.	Bridge: Acknowledge implication
	3.	Presence: Transition to shared goal or direction

Example:
	•	“We both didn’t have a clear path starting out”
→ “So we had to figure things out ourselves”
→ “That’s why we value building systems that actually work”

Invariant:

Never terminate on absence—always resolve into presence

⸻

2. Constraint Alignment Loop (CAL)

Purpose: Use shared limitations to coordinate action

Steps:
	1.	Identify shared constraint
	2.	Frame it as common ground
	3.	Convert to joint problem
	4.	Define cooperative action

Outcome:
	•	Constraint → coordination → execution

⸻

3. Opposition Dampening Protocol (ODP)

Purpose: Prevent instability from adversarial bonding

Steps:
	1.	Detect “us vs them” formation
	2.	Introduce neutral or positive anchor
	3.	Reframe identity away from opposition
	4.	Stabilize around shared constructive goal

Invariant:

Opposition may initiate bonding but cannot sustain it safely

⸻

4. Minimal Anchor Seeding (MAS)

Purpose: Rapid low-risk alignment in unknown environments

Method:
	•	Use low-stakes shared absences to establish initial rapport

Example:
	•	“None of us really knows how this will play out yet”

Effect:
	•	Reduces social friction
	•	Opens channel without commitment

⸻

5. Negative Signal Compression (NSC)

Purpose: Extract high-signal identity anchors from absence

Method:
	•	Compress shared absence into short-form identity marker

Example:
	•	“Self-taught”
	•	“Outside the system”

Effect:
	•	Fast recognition
	•	Memetic portability

